column350:
Somasila is a beautiful place for a 1-day/2-day trip (For a 2-day stay, one can stay at the Somasila Harita Resort (now run by private org)
Sri Lalitha Someswara Swamy Temple is a highly revered shrine dedicated to Lord Shiva. It is believed to have been built during the 7th century. Somasila is a well-known tourist attraction of Mahabubnagar that consists of 15 temples. These temples are dedicated to Lord Shiva and are enshrined with several Shivalingas.
The temple was shifted from old Somasila village to higher altitude to protect it from being submerged in Krishna water during the construction of Srisailam Dam. Its relocation is a marvel in itself. The surroundings are amazing with lot of views.

Far away from crowd. We visited on a Sunday and we could hardly see 2-3 familes. Food is a challenge, but if you go towards the View Point, you will find lot of local food hotels which serves good food. The road from Jadcherla is a smooth drive and we enjoyed our trip. There is boat (launch) ride available (15 mins - adult 50/- childred 30/-) You can pay double if the group agrees and stay in water for 30 mins. That is another amazing experience on Krishna Waters.

Now is the time to go before its highly promoted by tourism (krishna project) and you will see more people visiting.

column350:
The cable suspension bridge over the lake is a breathtaking sight to behold. As I stood on the bridge, I couldn't help but marvel at the sheer beauty of the nature that surrounded me.
The bridge itself was an engineering marvel, with its long span and slender cables that seemed to disappear into the horizon. As I walked across it, the gentle swaying motion added to the experience, making me feel like I was walking on air. Looking down, I could see the gentle ripples on the water's surface, and occasionally, a fish would leap out, adding to the serene atmosphere.
As I reached the middle of the bridge, I paused to take in the view. The lake spread out before me was nothing short of awe-inspiring. It was a moment that I will never forget.
The cable suspension bridge over the lake is a testament to the beauty of nature and the ingenuity of human engineering. It's a must-visit destination for anyone who loves the outdoors and wants to experience the breathtaking scenery that only nature can provide.

Went there very recently on January 2023 after watching many youtube & insta videos.
Note : FULL TANK UR CARS & BIKES AS THERE ARE NO PETROL PUMPS NEAR BY FOR AROUND 15 KMS.
The place is good surrounded by hills but no proper maintenance.
we couldn’t get into the water as the water looks totally green filled with lots & lots of Algae.
Price :The boat ride is quite expensive they are charging 2000 rs/- for one boat for 20 mins ride .
we paid 1000 Rs . For 3 people which i felt was quite expensive .
Food : As shown in few youtube videos we can see many locals having food stalls . But didnt dare to eat the fish there as we saw they are not cleaning the fish properly & not maintaining proper hygiene standards.( what i felt )
Try to go there early mornings as it was too hot & sunny even in January ☀️
It might be better if we would have visited in rainy season.
My Final thought 💭 I would not recommend this place 👎🏻 instead u can visit komati chervu (siddipet ) which is far better & beautiful & well maintained.
Hope this review is helpful .

column350:
Original review: 9th Sept 2018
Edited & updated: 14th July 2022

This waterfall is actually known as Jin Thogu Waterfall.

One has to trek 12-14 km from Alubaka to reach the waterfall.
3km to reach the village either Tippaiguda, Mutharam or Seetarampur.
8 km of dense forest trek and
Final 1 - 3 km to reach the waterfall crossing streams and boulders.

There are 5 waterfalls in all. They are
1. Kothi Kuntla Vagu
2. Tadapala Vagu
3. Ingel Thogu
4. Jin Thogu
5. Chalamala Vagu
These 5 are the top highest waterfalls in Telangana.

Note -
1. The local residents of Tippaiguda, Mutharam and Seetarampur call this group of  5 waterfalls as Gaddalasari Waterfall. Gaddalasari is approachable from Alubaka.

2. Mutyala Dhara OR Muthyam Dhara  is approachable from Veerabhadravaram. This is the 7th highest waterfall in Telangana.

3. Muthyam Dhara and Gaddalasari are 2 different waterfalls.

I recently had the opportunity to visit the Octopus View Point at Srisailam, and it was a fantastic experience. The viewpoint offers a stunning view of the backwaters of the Krishna River, surrounded by hills and forests.

The viewpoint is well-maintained and the location is easily accessible, and there is ample parking space available.

The view from the Octopus View Point is breathtaking, with the river and its backwaters creating a serene and peaceful ambiance. The lush greenery of the surrounding hills and forests adds to the natural beauty of the location.

The Octopus View Point is an ideal spot for nature lovers and photographers. The viewpoint offers a perfect vantage point to capture stunning photographs of the river and the surrounding hills. It's also an excellent spot to relax and unwind, away from the hustle and bustle of the city.

Overall, I would highly recommend a visit to the Octopus View Point at Srisailam to anyone visiting the area. The natural beauty of the location and the peaceful ambiance make it an ideal spot to rejuvenate and connect with nature.

Kondapochamma Reservoir is a major irrigation project in Telangana state, located in the Nalgonda district. The reservoir is built on the Kondapochamma River and is one of the largest water bodies in the state. Here is a review of the Kondapochamma Reservoir based on its features:

Irrigation: The main purpose of the reservoir is to provide irrigation to the surrounding agricultural lands. The reservoir has a storage capacity of 15 tmcft and can irrigate an area of 1.2 lakh acres.

Drinking water: The reservoir also provides drinking water to the nearby villages and towns. The water is treated and supplied through pipelines to the villages.

Tourism: The reservoir is a popular tourist destination in the region. It offers a serene environment, and visitors can enjoy boating, fishing, and other water activities.

Dam: The Kondapochamma Reservoir is built with a 46-meter high earthen dam, which is a major engineering feat.

Location: The reservoir is located in a picturesque location surrounded by hills and forests, making it an ideal spot for a day trip or weekend getaway.

Overall, Kondapochamma Reservoir is an important irrigation project and a popular tourist destination in Telangana state. The reservoir has greatly helped in increasing agricultural productivity in the region and providing drinking water to the local communities.

column350:
Malwala Palace was built in 1845 and is located in Hyderabad, telangana, India. Malwala Palace was located along the road leading towards east from Charminar. It was constructed in Mughal and Rajasthani style and in Hyderabadi courtyard style, was known for its richly carved. wooden pavilion. Other than Raja Bhagwandas Bagh Pavilion, Malwala Palace was the only other palace in Hyderabad having a wooden pavilion.Barring the grand gateway, the entire palace complex has been demolished in August 2000 and a shopping mall has been built in its place.

The Malwalas were responsible for the revenue records of the Nizam's dominions. The palace belonged to a noble family of Dewan Chandulal, the Malwala or the custodians of the Revenue Records (Daftar -i- Mal) of the erstwhile Hyderabad State. Built in the early 18th century by the noble Sagar Mall during the reign of first nizam in 1724, this was one of the very few palaces of Hyderabad built in the Mughal and Rajasthani styles of architecture. It acquired the name Malwala as Sagar Mall was the custodian of revenue records (maal) in hyderabad state. At the time department of revenue was held by the Mathur Kayastha family or Malwala family. During the 1940s, at the time of one of the family descendants, Raja Dharam Karan, the grandeur of the palace was resplendent and was noted for its glory and power.

It was an exquisite Diwan Khana made of huge arches in lacquered wood and painted with vegetable dyes and two galleries about 80 m in length flanking the Diwan Khana on each side constructed with Rangoon teak rafters. The galleries housed priceless collection of antique Indian art and artifacts. The palace also had a library, which boasted of a collection of rare books and manuscripts from the 10th century A.D. It is one of the few wooden edifices in the city, a double-storeyed mansion with inner courtyards, with its ornamental archway entrance rich in stucco work and a fountain at the centre. There were wooden pavilions on two sides and overhanging wooden balconies with intricate patterns in Rajasthani and Mughal architectural styles. The palace had two wings, the eastern part used for official business, celebrations and social functions and the western one for residential purpose. The eastern part extended to 2460 square metres with a beautiful cistern standing in the middle of the vast courtyard. It consisted of a series of galleries in two floors and a wooden pavilion, which like the Diwan-i-Khas of the Delhi Fort is "an oriental magnificence in wood." Vegetable dyes were used for decorating the lacquered wood and the walls. Tragedy struck the Malwala Palace, a protected heritage building, having rare wooden pavilion considered the "bride" among the garland of palaces around Charminar when the major portion as important as the "heart" was reduced to rubble in 2000. The demolition occurred after disputes between a sections of the owners of the palace, some in collusion with real estate developers and politicians over maintaining heritage status of the building.

column350:
This is a clean zoo with lots of animals of various species. Best time to visit is in the morning between 9AM and 10AM. It takes around 2-3 hours to see everything. They also offer toy train ride and Lion, Tiger, Bear and Deer safari at 75Rs per person in AC and Non-AC buses. Entry for kids below 3 years is free.
Improvements needed - Drinking water. There are only 2-3 drinking water fountains available and none of them were working. They also have a place where they charge 5Rs to fill water bottle and that too was broken.
Eating area - There is no proper restaurant or seating area. They don't even have a hand wash area. Do they expect people to wash hands in the open with their own water bottles or eat with dirty hands after roaming around half the zoo?
Directions/Information - There are no clear directions or route to take for optimal viewing experience. Many animals didn't even have an info board outside the enclosure with their names and details.

column328:
Snow World is an indoor snow park located in Hyderabad, India. It is one of the largest snow parks in India and offers visitors the opportunity to experience the thrill of playing in the snow, even in a tropical climate.

Snow World is an ideal destination for families, especially during the hot summer months, as it provides a cool and refreshing escape from the heat. The park is equipped with state-of-the-art technology, including snow-making machines, to ensure that visitors can enjoy a real winter wonderland experience.

Visitors can participate in a variety of activities, including snowboarding, ice-skating, and sledding, and there is also a separate area for children to play and build snowmen. The park also has a number of restaurants and cafes, offering a range of food and drinks, so visitors can relax and enjoy a meal while taking a break from the snow.

Snow World is a popular tourist destination and attracts visitors from all over India, as well as from overseas. The park is well-maintained and has adequate parking facilities for private vehicles. Visitors are required to follow a dress code, which requires them to wear warm clothing and winter gear, such as jackets, gloves, and boots, which are available for rent at the park.

Whether you're looking for a fun day out with the family or simply want to experience the thrill of playing in the snow, Snow World is a must-visit destination in Hyderabad. The park offers a unique and exciting experience, and its cool and refreshing environment is sure to make it a memorable experience for all visitors.

column350:
B.M. Birla Science Museum is a science museum located in Hyderabad, India. It is part of the Birla Science Centre and is one of the most popular science museums in South India. The museum was established in 1991 and is named after the industrialist and philanthropist, B.M. Birla.

The museum offers a unique and interactive experience for visitors, with a range of exhibits and displays showcasing the wonders of science and technology. The museum has several galleries, including the Earth and Universe Gallery, which displays the history of the universe and the evolution of life on earth.

The museum also has a hall of popular science, which showcases the latest developments in science and technology, including new inventions, innovations, and breakthroughs. The museum has a range of interactive exhibits, including hands-on science experiments, simulations, and virtual reality experiences, which allow visitors to learn about science in a fun and engaging way.

The B.M. Birla Science Museum also has a planetarium, which offers daily shows that take visitors on a journey through the universe. The planetarium has a state-of-the-art digital projection system and provides visitors with an immersive experience, bringing the wonders of the universe to life.

The museum is a popular destination for families and school groups, and it offers a range of educational programs and workshops for students of all ages. The museum is well-maintained, and it has adequate parking facilities for private vehicles.

Whether you're a science enthusiast or simply looking for a fun and educational day out, the B.M. Birla Science Museum is a must-visit destination in Hyderabad. The museum's interactive exhibits, planetarium shows, and educational programs provide a fascinating and enriching experience for all visitors.

column350:
I recently visited Pochampally village and was blown away by its charm and beauty. The village is known for its handloom weaving, and it was fascinating to see the weavers at work, creating intricate and beautiful designs.

The village is also home to a variety of temples and monuments, which provided a glimpse into the rich cultural heritage of the region. I particularly enjoyed visiting the Sri Seetha Rama Chandra Swamy temple, which was both beautiful and peaceful.

What stood out to me the most was the warm hospitality of the locals. They were friendly and welcoming, and went out of their way to make me feel at home.

Overall, my experience at Pochampally village was truly unforgettable. I would highly recommend this village to anyone looking for a unique and enriching cultural experience in Telangana. Don't forget to pick up some beautiful handloom textiles as souvenirs!

column328:
This should be renamed peacock park as this is the main attraction here. These beautiful creatures are abundant and see less and less shy about coming close to humans.

Outside the park there is a big jogging ring that seems to be open to the public, however there are very, very, very few entrance points and you may walk 1km or so before you can find one.
The path is packed dirt, and is leveled and safe for the most part. Just be on the lookout of dog feces which are all over the track. It would be nice if they created a few RO water stations throughout the track for the community.  There is really only one entrance point, that's a bit negative for such a huge park.

The gardens are constantly watered by workers and well kept. The entrance fee is nominal ( around ₹50 ) and this park is absolutely giant. You could easily spent a couple hours in here.

Worth visiting to take a break from the concrete jungle.

column328:
It’s an old fort and of this city and standing still by showing off its old history. One would need half a day to completely explore this complex.

For elders it is bit difficult to climb to the top. But it’s quite interesting. Complex is big and takes time to explore. While going take sufficient water and wear comfortable dress which makes you walk easily.

Parking is a mess here.  There is no dedicated parking.  You have to park outside. In the crowded days if you go late you may not get the parking.

Tickets are Available online.  This could save you time in the queue.

Definitely it’s a worth the visit if you are in and around Hyderabad.
